{{US}}
'''{{PAGENAME}}''' involves parents or caregivers balancing the need to accumulate resources for the disabled adult child (DAC) while at the same time maximizing available government benefits. This article first covers the most common government programs that are available, followed by strategies for saving and investing that minimize conflict with needs based government programs.

The focus is primarily on disabilities acquired from birth or other medical conditions, typically in childhood or young adulthood. The article does not cover income replacement programs due to disability, such as SSDI earned through work credits, workers' compensation, and private disability insurance.

== Overview ==

Accumulating resources while maximizing government benefits are two goals that can sometimes be in tension with each other. For instance, allocating assets and investments in the disabled adult's name could disqualify them from some government programs, such as Supplemental Security Income (SSI) and Medicaid, both of which serve disabled adults. The result can be that the applicable government agencies view any form of material personal savings as indicating that the disabled adult has enough personal resources to not need government benefits.

In order to achieve these sometimes conflicting objectives, parents will often use available tools, such as supplemental needs trusts (SNTs) and Achieving a Better Life Experience (ABLE) accounts, that allow both for the accumulation of resources for the disabled adult, while at the same time maintaining benefit eligibility. Implementing these tools and strategies can be complex and expensive, and may need specialized legal help to set up and administer.

==Income assistance programs available for disabled adults==

===Supplemental Security Income (SSI)===
[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi Supplemental Security Income (SSI)] is the most common non-work history based disability income benefit. It is administered federally by the [https://www.ssa.gov/ Social Security Administration (SSA)] but funded by general revenues, not the Social Security Fund. In order to receive SSI you must have little to no income, very little financial assets and a qualifying disability.

SSI limits the amount of income a potential beneficiary can receive. The amount depends on the type of income. The SSA defines four primary types of income applicable to SSI:<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/text-income-ussi.htm SSA-Understanding Supplemental Security Income SSI Income -- 2025 Edition]</ref><ref group="note">Alternatively income can be categorized as "earned" or "unearned", and in-kind support and maintenance and deemed income are forms of unearned income, along with applicable government benefits, passive income from interest, dividends, and so on.</ref>

* '''Earned income''' is wages, net earnings from self–employment, certain royalties, honoraria, and sheltered workshop payments.
* '''Unearned income''' is all income that is not earned, such as Social Security benefits, pensions, State disability payments, unemployment benefits, interest income, dividends, and cash from friends and relatives.
* '''In-kind income''' is food, shelter, or both that you get for free or for less than its fair market value. (As of September 30, 2024 food is no longer considered in-kind income.)
* '''Deemed income''' is the part of the income of your spouse with whom you live, your parent(s) with whom you live, or your sponsor (if you are not a US citizen), used to compute your SSI benefit amount.

The maximum monthly SSI payment (Federal Benefit Rate or FBR) for 2025 is $967 and $994 for 2026,<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/oact/cola/SSI.html SSA-SSI Federal Payment Amounts For 2026]</ref> and $1,450 and $1,491 for married couples.<ref group="note">Both members of married couple must be disabled.</ref> Some states offer additional SSI, sometimes referred to as SSP (state supplemental payment).<ref>[https://www.atticus.com/advice/disability-help-by-state/ssi-supplemental-payments-by-state Atticus-SSI Supplemental Payments by State]</ref> SSI benefits are exempt from federal or state income tax.

The base federal SSI amount is reduced by countable income dollar for dollar. Countable income is non-excludable income from the four income categories above that is considered available for basic needs and reduces the monthly SSI payment. The following income is considered excludable (non-countable):<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/text-income-ussi.htm SSA-Understanding Supplemental Security Income SSI Income -- 2025 Edition]</ref>

*The first $20 of most income received in a month;
*The first $65 of earnings and one–half of earnings over $65 received in a month;
*The value of Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (food stamps) received;
*Income tax refunds;
*Home energy assistance;
*Assistance based on need funded by a State or local government, or an Indian tribe;
*Small amounts of income received irregularly or infrequently;
*Interest or dividends earned on countable resources or resources excluded under other Federal laws;
*Grants, scholarships, fellowships, or gifts used for tuition and educational expenses;
*Food or shelter based on need provided by nonprofit agencies;
*Loans to you (cash or in–kind) that you have to repay;
*Money someone else spends to pay your expenses for items other than food or shelter (for example, someone pays your telephone or medical bills);
*Income set aside under a Plan to Achieve Self-Support (PASS). See the SSI Spotlight on Plan to Achieve Self–Support;
*Earnings up to $2,350 per month to a maximum of $9,460 per year (effective January 2025) for a student under age 22. See the Spotlight on the Student Earned Income Exclusion on Student Earned Income Exclusion;
*The cost of impairment–related work expenses for items or services that a disabled person needs in order to work. See the SSI Spotlight on Impairment–Related Work Expenses;
*The cost of work expenses that a blind person incurs in order to work. See the SSI Spotlight on Special SSI Rule for Blind People Who Work;
*Disaster assistance;
*The first $2,000 of compensation received per calendar year for participating in certain clinical trials;
*Refundable Federal and advanced tax credits received on or after January 1, 2010; and
*Certain exclusions on Indian trust fund payments paid to American Indians who are members of a federally recognized tribe.

The calculations for countable income are somewhat complex,<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/text-income-ussi.htm SSA-Understanding Supplemental Security Income SSI Income -- 2025 Edition]</ref> but as a general rule only a portion of earned income is included as countable income, whereas unearned, in-kind and deemed income are mostly countable income.

Given the rules around unearned and in-kind income, it is rarely a good idea to give cash directly to the disabled adult child, whether as a gift or reimbursing for an expense. These cash inflows are considered countable income and reduce that month's SSI payment dollar for dollar. It is almost always better for the parent or other party to pay for the item directly. By directly paying an allowable expense (not basic support and maintenance) the expense will not be countable. However, if a parent or third party directly pays basic support and maintenance, that is considered in-kind support and maintenance and is countable.

In addition, unreimbursed housing provided by a parent or other party to the disabled adult child is considered in-kind income, and also reduces the monthly SSI payment, up to a maximum one third reduction of the payment.<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/spotlights/spot-living-arrangements.htm SSA-SPOTLIGHT ON LIVING ARRANGEMENTS -- 2025 Edition]</ref> You can avoid this reduction by charging the disabled adult child a reasonable fixed monthly rent, generally approximating FMV, based on a set documented agreement.<ref>[https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/blog/avoiding-ssi-reductions-when-an-adult-with-disabilities-lives-with-family/ Special Needs Alliance - Avoiding SSI Reductions When An Adult With Disabilities Lives With Family]</ref><ref group="note">If the reasonable FMV based rent exceeds the maximum SSI payment, then this may be viewed as in-kind support and cause a one-third SSI payment reduction. Paying the excess rent out of an ABLE account may be one way to address this. Seek a qualified professional for advice on this, or consult with SSA directly for guidance.</ref> An alternative, if the disabled adult child lives in a home with others, is to implement a family, fair, or pro-rata share arrangement, so that the child shares in an equal portion of applicable household expenses, which includes rent or mortgage, property tax, home insurance, utilities such as electricity, heat and gas and household grocery food items.<ref group="note">As of October 2024 providing food is no longer considered in kind income. It appears that it also may be excluded from family and fair share arrangements. Source: [https://www.stetson.edu/law/conferences/snt/media/pt_3_brown_mat.pdf Ken Brown-Stetson University-2024 Supplemental Security Income (SSI) Program Update] (November 2025).</ref> The average total of those monthly expenses should be divided equally among the number of members and the resulting amount is the family or fair share allocation. On a monthly basis the disabled adult child would reimburse the homeowner or head of household the family share allocation.<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/text-living-ussi.htm SSA-SUPPLEMENTAL SECURITY INCOME (SSI) LIVING ARRANGEMENTS]</ref> If the family share allocation exceeds the maximum SSI payment, then the excess reimbursement would be considered in-kind income and would reduce the SSI payment. One strategy to avoid SSI payment reduction would be to pay the excess of the family share amount over the SSI payment out of an ABLE account.<ref>[https://www.fletchertilton.com/using-able-accounts-to-avoid-a-one-third-loss-in-ssi/ Using ABLE Accounts to Avoid a One Third Loss in SSI]</ref> A family share agreement and amount should be reported to SSA.

SSI also has strict asset (resource) limits. The financial resource limits are $2,000 for single adults and $3,000 for couples (both disabled).<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/spotlights/spot-resources.htm SSA-SPOTLIGHT ON RESOURCES -- 2025 Edition]</ref> This includes cash, bank accounts, taxable investment accounts and most other liquid financial assets. These are considered countable resources and if they exceed the resource limit threshold ($2,000) they can disqualify the recipient from SSI eligibility. Retirement accounts, such as traditional or Roth IRAs or 401ks, are also generally considered countable resources.<ref>[https://www.avvo.com/legal-answers/can-an-ira-account-that-has-not-been-used-count-ag-5339065.html Avvo-Can an IRA account that has not been used count against SSI?]</ref><ref group="note">There may be cases where certain defined benefit plans that are not paying out and not currently accessible by the employer are not considered countable. Also, there have been anecdotal reports of some SSA offices occasionally ignoring IRAs or Roths in the SSI application process. The theoretical danger here is SSA could subsequently perform an audit and deem the retirement account a countable resource, resulting the recipient having to pay back prior benefits as overpayments.</ref> Some resources are exceptions and not considered countable, such as a primary home, one car, household goods and other similar tangible assets.<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/spotlights/spot-resources.htm SSA-SPOTLIGHT ON RESOURCES -- 2025 Edition]</ref>

From a countable income and resource perspective, college [[529 plan|529 plans]] are somewhat of a mixed bag. The key determinant is ownership. If the adult child owns the account then it is countable as a resource asset. If a parent or relative owns the account it is not countable. In terms of distributions from an account owned by a parent or relative, direct payment for tuition and books from a 529 is not countable, but payment for housing from the 529 is likely countable (consult state specific rules). A [[529-ABLE plan|529 ABLE]] account is a better and more flexible option.

The application process for SSI can be long and difficult. It is estimated that approximately one in three applicants is approved.<ref>[https://usafacts.org/data-projects/disability-benefit-process USA Facts - What is the approval rate for Social Security Disability Benefits?]</ref> A candidate can be rejected for technical reasons (non-medical) or medical reasons<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/disability/professionals/bluebook/AdultListings.htm SSA-Disability Evaluation Under Social Security]</ref> (does not meet the definition of disabled). For those that do meet technical qualifications, approximately one in two qualifies for medical reasons as disabled. Breaking this down further, 38% of applicants who meet technical requirements are accepted initially, but 53% of applicants who appeal that decision are ultimately approved. The use of a disability attorney can often increase the chances of approval on appeal. These attorneys will often work on contingency, if successful charging a percentage of eligible SSI back pay from date of initial application. In some cases where the need is significant and eligibility seemingly clear cut a [https://www.ssa.gov/compassionateallowances/ compassionate allowance] acceptance is available.

The average time of review and approval nationally is about 200-230 days, but with some states taking longer, such as Texas, coming in at 415 days.<ref group="note">Source: [https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-01801.html How long does it take to get a decision after I apply for disability benefits?], SSA, as of October 2025.</ref> With appeals, the process can extend longer. In these cases the payment, which is payable back to the application date, can significantly exceed the $2,000 SSI resource limit. The back payment is typically broken up into several periodic payments. There are specific rules and guidance for how to handle these payments and the resulting temporary asset balance increases over the $2000 limit. Failing to follow them can lead to a reduction or suspension of benefits. One way to handle this is to deposit the back payments in a separate savings account and spend down the resources on permissible expenses.<ref>[https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/blog/managing-retroactive-ssi-benefits/ SNA-Managing Retroactive SSI Benefits]</ref> Another work around is to move them into a 529-ABLE account.

In many cases with SSI, as is the case for other Social Security programs, including SSDI-DAC (see below), there is a [https://www.ssa.gov/payee/ representative payee] program, which allows for others (often a parent with a disabled adult child) to manage the SSI or other Social Security benefit if the beneficiary is unable to manage it themselves. A Durable Power of Attorney or other legal instrument won’t work for this, only a representative payee designation. In many cases a representative payee bank account can be set up to receive the monthly SSI payment.

An additional benefit of SSI is that in most states it also qualifies the recipient for Medicaid. However, Medicaid is administered by the states, so the specifics vary from state to state. You can find more on this in the [[#Medicaid|Medicaid]] section below.

Another benefit of qualifying for SSI (or SSDI-DAC) is you automatically meet the disability definition required to be an [https://greenleaftrust.com/missives/more-expansive-eligible-designated-beneficiary-definition/ Eligible Designated Beneficiary (EDB)] for purposes of [[Inheriting an IRA|inherited IRA]] [[Required Minimum Distribution|required minimum distributions]], which allows for a lifetime RMD stretch instead of 10 year IRA distribution period.

===Social Security Disability Income - Disabled Adult Child (SSDI-DAC)===
The [https://www.atticus.com/advice/general/disabled-adult-child-benefits Disabled Adult Child]<ref group="note">SSA formally uses the term "Child's Insurance Benefits (CIB)" for all dependents (including adult disabled children). See: [https://www.ssa.gov/redbook/eng/glossary.htm#:~:text=A%2520person%2520with%2520a%2520qualifying,Child%2520(DAC)%2520benefits.%E2%80%9D SSA Redbook]</ref> benefit is part of the [https://www.ssa.gov/disability Social Security Disability Insurance] program. Unlike most SSDI recipients whose benefits are based on their work history, the DAC benefit is based on the beneficiary's parent eligibility. In order to qualify for DAC, the person must be disabled, with the disability starting before age 22, and have a parent who is receiving Social Security retirement or disability benefits, or who has died but was insured under Social Security at the time of death.<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/pubs/EN-05-10026.pdf SSA-5 Benefits For Children With Disabilities 2025]</ref>

Unlike SSI, DAC is not a means based program, so there are no asset or resource tests, and no countable income test. However, enough earned or work related income may disqualify you from DAC by demonstrating the recipient is no longer disabled.

* DACs are subject to Continuing Disability Reviews (CDRs) just like other SSDI recipients.
* If a DAC earns above the Substantial Gainful Activity (SGA) threshold ($1,550/month in 2025 for non-blind individuals), SSA can determine they are no longer disabled, ending benefits.
* However, SSA may allow a Trial Work Period (TWP) and Extended Period of Eligibility (EPE) for those attempting work.

In most cases if the DAC gets married they will be disqualified for SSDI-DAC benefits, unless the spouse is also on SSDI under their own disability.

Typically, if a potential beneficiary has already qualified for SSI before age 22, they will likely be eligible for DAC as soon as a parent files and is approved for Social Security retirement benefits.  Otherwise, the SSDI application process and disability criteria is the same as for SSI.  The DAC benefit is up to 50% of the parent's PIA (primary insurance amount), subject to family maximums.<ref>[https://www.maximizemysocialsecurity.com/ask-larry/how-will-my-wifes-and-disabled-childs-benefits-be-calculated-when-i-apply-my-benefits How Will My Wife's And Disabled Child's Benefits Be Calculated When I Apply For My Benefits?]</ref> This amount remains the same whether the parent files for Social Security retirement benefits before or after age 67. In other words, unlike retirement benefits which decrease if you file earlier than full retirement age, and increase if you file later than full retirement age, the DAC benefit remains at (up to) 50% of your full retirement age benefit (PIA-adjusted for inflation), regardless of filing age. In addition to the DAC benefit, the non-filing parent may be eligible for child-in-care spousal benefits, which can be up to another 50% of the retiring parent's PIA, subject to [https://www.ssa.gov/oact/cola/familymax.html family maximum] limits.<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/20/229.48 Cornell Law-Family Maximum]</ref><ref group="note">In practice the family maximum typically caps out between 150% and 188% of PIA. Source: [https://www.helpwithmysocialsecurity.com/post/family-maximum-benefit Maximize my Social Security-Family Maximum]</ref> If a qualifying parent has died, the benefit increases to 75% of deceased parent's PIA, again subject to family maximums.<ref>[https://www.maximizemysocialsecurity.com/ask-larry/will-my-disabled-child-receive-50-my-age-62-rate-or-my-full-retirement-age-rate Maximize my Social Security - Will My Disabled Child Receive 50% Of My Age 62 Rate Or My Full Retirement Age Rate?]</ref>

One unique aspect of spousal child-in-care benefits is the spouse does not need to apply for their own benefit to get the child-in-care spousal benefit. This is an exception to the deemed filing rule that went into effect in 2016.<ref group="note">"Exceptions to deemed filing:

Deemed filing applies to retirement benefits, not survivor's benefits. If you are a spouse, you may start your survivor benefit independently of your retirement benefit. Deemed filing also does not apply if you receive spouse's benefits and are entitled to disability, ''or if you are receiving spousal benefits because you are caring for the retired worker’s child.'' Source: [https://www.ssa.gov/benefits/retirement/planner/claiming.html SSA - Filing Rules for Retirement and Spouses Benefits].</ref> Also, there is also no minimum age for receiving child-in-care spousal benefits.<ref group="note">"Another requirement is that the spouse must be at least age 62 ''or have a qualifying child in her/his care. By a qualifying child, we mean a child who is under age 16 or who receives Social Security disability benefits.''" Source: [https://www.ssa.gov/oact/quickcalc/spouse.html SSA-Social Security Benefits-Benefits for Spouses].</ref>

The [https://opensocialsecurity.com/ Open Social Security] calculator by Mike Piper (also known as Oblivious Investor) helps to identify optimal social security filing strategies, including the impact of DAC and child-in-care spousal benefits. The following are considerations when evaluating alternative strategies:

* The DAC payment is 50% of the primary insurance amount (PIA) while the filing parent is alive. This is true regardless of the parent's filing age. So while filing early does reduce the parent's base social security amount, it does not reduce the DAC payment.
* The same is true for spousal child-in-care, if eligible. The additional 50% (subject to family maximums), is based upon the filer's PIA, regardless of whether the filing parent retires before or after full retirement age.
* If a spouse receives spousal child-in-care benefits, the spouse can continue to defer filing on their own work record and allow their regular benefit to grow.
* The above factors can make filing earlier, for at least one parent, more advantageous.
* Like all social security payments, earned income can reduce or eliminate social security payments prior to full retirement age (FRA) due to the [https://www.ssa.gov/oact/cola/rtea.html Social Security earnings test], including child-in-care spousal payments, so having the second spouse still working can reduce the benefit of filing early, all else being equal.
* Once the second spouse files, then the adult child DAC payment will be based on 50% of the higher of the two PIAs. The DAC payment does not stack the two PIAs.
* Unlike the DAC payment, the family maximum does stack once both parents file, subject to combined family maximum limits. But the second spouse will lose child-in-care spousal benefits.
* If a qualifying parent has died, the child benefit increases to 75% of the deceased parent's PIA, again subject to family maximums. At that time, the child-in-care spousal benefit (if applicable) will terminate, but the surviving spouse may become eligible for a mother or father benefit, which is also equal to 75% of the deceased spouse's PIA.
* Ultimately, to the extent applicable, you should also factor in the lost SSI payments when evaluating the optimal filing strategy. The Open Social Security calculator does not do this (but this is noted on the site). You can approximate the impact by adding back the total SSI payments that would be lost due to DAC.
* One spouse filing earlier has the advantage of making the adult child eligible for Medicare sooner (see below).

An additional benefit of DAC is that after receiving DAC for 24 months, recipients are typically also eligible for Medicare. DAC beneficiaries who transition from SSI may retain Medicaid under the federal DAC protection rules, even if SSI stops<ref>[https://specialneedsanswers.com/dont-let-social-security-disabled-adult-childrens-benefits-interfere-with--medicaid-benefits-13934 Special needs answers - Don't Let DAC Benefits Interfere With Medicaid, SSI]</ref> or qualify under the applicable state's AABD or ABD rules (see [[#Medicaid|Medicaid]] section below).

SSDI-DAC benefits are [[Taxation of Social Security benefits|taxable under federal income tax]] in the same was as other Social Security Income, with thresholds leading to 50% and 85% of benefits becoming taxable.

==Medical assistance programs for disabled adults==

===Medicaid===
[https://www.medicaid.gov/ Medicaid] is government provided health insurance for low income, disabled and certain elderly participants. It is funded jointly by the federal government and state governments, and is administered by the states. Medicaid programs usually have either no or very low out of pocket participant payments. Medicaid reimbursement rates to providers are often lower than private insurance or Medicare. As a result, some providers will not accept Medicaid, so provider choices may be limited. However, most hospitals do accept Medicaid.

As previously mentioned, SSI often qualifies participants for Medicaid. In some states it is automatic. In other states the participant must apply but is otherwise eligible. In eight states (as of October 2024)<ref group="note">The states are: Connecticut, Hawaii, Illinois, Minnesota, Missouri, New Hampshire, North Dakota, and Virginia.</ref> there are individual (and potentially more restrictive) criteria that may not exactly align with SSI eligibility. These are referred to as 209(b) states.<ref>[https://www.disabilitysecrets.com/resources/health-care/medicare/which-states-automatically-grant-med#:~:text=States%20With%20Their%20Own%20Medicaid,Medicaid%20income%20and%20asset%20limits. Disability Secrets - Which States Automatically Grant Medicaid With SSI Disability?]</ref><ref>[https://www.kff.org/medicaid/what-are-the-primary-medicaid-eligibility-pathways-for-dual-eligible-individuals/#9d74b0a1-a574-4585-8107-cd0ce520e779 KFF-What Are the Primary Medicaid Eligibility Pathways for Dual-Eligible Individuals?]</ref> This is particularly important if the disabled adult child moves to a different state, which could require applying again.

Like SSI, Medicaid is usually means tested, and in most states the asset and resource maximums are similar to SSI. However, in a few states the limits are higher, and as of 2025 California and Arizona have no asset or resource limit,<ref>[https://www.kff.org/medicaid/state-indicator/medicaid-eligibility-through-the-aged-blind-disabled-pathway/?currentTimeframe=0&sortModel=%7B%22colId%22:%22Location%22,%22sort%22:%22asc%22%7D KFF - Medicaid Eligibility for SSI Enrollees and Optional Seniors & People with Disabilities Up To 100% FPL]</ref> although in 2026 California will once again have an asset limit of $130,000 for individuals and $65,000 for each additional eligible house member.<ref>[https://canhr.org/2026-asset-limit-reinstatement-frequently-asked-questions/ CANHR-2026 ASSET LIMIT REINSTATEMENT FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS]</ref>

In some instances a disabled recipient can be eligible for Medicaid but not SSI. These circumstances tend to vary by state. One instance is when a recipient remains in Medicaid while receiving DAC, during the two year Medicare waiting period, and sometimes even after the waiting period. In some instances where an individual may not be eligible for SSI, they may be eligible based on the state's assistance for aged, blind and disabled criteria (AABD or ABD).<ref>[https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/hawaii/Haw-Code-R-SS-17-658-7 Cornell Law-Hawaii - Haw. Code R. § 17-658-7 - State financial assistance for aged, blind, and disabled individuals]</ref><ref>[https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=30370 Illinois-IDHS-Aid to the Aged, Blind, and Disabled (AABD)]</ref><ref>[https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Aged-Blind-or-Disabled.aspx Nebraska - DHHS - Aid To The Aged, Blind, Or Disabled]</ref>

In most states<ref>[https://www.kff.org/medicaid/state-indicator/medicaid-eligibility-through-buy-in-programs-for-working-people-with-disabilities/?currentTimeframe=0&sortModel=%7B%22colId%22:%22Location%22,%22sort%22:%22asc%22%7D KFF-Medicaid Eligibility through Buy-In Programs for Working People with Disabilities]</ref> Medicaid Buy In programs<ref>[https://www.dol.gov/sites/dolgov/files/odep/topics/medicaidbuyinqaf.pdf Dept of Labor - Medicaid buy in]</ref> are available for disabled adults who work and otherwise would not qualify due to their incomes. The income and asset requirements tend to be more lenient than basic Medicaid, but the requirements vary by state. In states that have enacted the [https://www.healthcare.gov/medicaid-chip/medicaid-expansion-and-you/ ACA Medicaid expansion], low income individuals can sign up for Medicaid even if they are not disabled.<ref>[https://www.kff.org/medicaid/status-of-state-medicaid-expansion-decisions/ KFF-Status of State Medicaid Expansion Decisions]</ref>

===Medicare===
[[Medicare]] is a federal health insurance program primarily for those aged 65 and over. However, some disabled individuals are eligible for Medicare, such as participants in SSDI-DAC, after a two year waiting period. Medicare can be advantageous compared to Medicaid in that there are no means tests, and Medicare plans are typically more widely accepted than Medicaid.

In the case of DAC participants on Medicare, they can either enroll in a traditional Medicare or a [https://medicareadvocacy.org/medicare-info/medicare-advantage/ Medicare Advantage] plan. In addition, some participants may also be enrolled in Medicaid and participate in a Medicare Advantage/Medicaid dual use plan.<ref>[https://www.cms.gov/medicare/enrollment-renewal/special-needs-plans/dual-eligible CMS-Dual Eligible Special Needs Plans (D-SNPs)]</ref><ref>[https://www.cms.gov/files/document/beneficiaries-dually-eligible-medicare-medicaid.pdf CMS-Beneficiaries Dually Eligible for Medicare & Medicaid]</ref> In those cases state specific Medicaid means tests may still apply. The advantage of having both is the wider acceptance of Medicare, and little or no out of pocket expenses with Medicaid, especially in hospital or institutional settings. Also, similar to some Medicare Advantage plans, the dual use plans will often come with pre-loaded debit cards with nominal amounts for specific health related expenditures.

Medicare recipients with low income and resources may be able to qualify for a [https://www.medicare.gov/basics/costs/help/medicare-savings-programs Medicaid Savings Program]. The application is submitted at the state level. These programs help pay for Medicare [https://www.medicare.gov/providers-services/original-medicare/part-a Part A] (hospital Insurance) and [https://www.medicare.gov/providers-services/original-medicare/part-b Part B] (Medical Insurance) premiums, as well as potentially co-pays, deductibles and co-insurance. Those on Medicare with lower incomes may also be eligible for the [https://www.medicare.gov/publications/12203-medicares-extra-help-program.pdf Extra Help] program, which provides assistance for Medicare [https://www.medicare.gov/health-drug-plans/part-d Part D] prescription drugs.

===Medicaid waiver services===
[https://www.cms.gov/training-education/partner-outreach-resources/american-indian-alaska-native/ltss-ta-center/information/state-medicaid-plans-and-waivers Medicaid waiver services] are state run programs that provide expanded home based and community based care for disabled adults.<ref>[https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/home-community-based-services/home-community-based-services-authorities/home-community-based-services-1915c Medicaid-Home & Community-Based Services 1915(c)]</ref> The "waiver" allows Medicaid to provide these services outside of an institutional setting. In some instances parents and family members can be compensated for providing in-home services to the disabled adult child. These services are referred to as home and community based care - [https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/home-community-based-services/home-community-based-services-authorities/home-community-based-services-1915c (HCBS) 1915(c) services]. These programs typically have very specific qualifications and can often have very long wait lists, sometimes taking decades to be accepted. It is a good idea to get on these wait lists as soon as you realize your child has a disability. In cases deemed to be emergencies, an emergency waiver may be issued.

The qualifications for the program, the types of programs and the level of means testing is state specific.<ref>[https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/section-1115-demo/demonstration-and-waiver-list Medicaid-State Waivers List]</ref> Typically the means testing criteria are less strict than basic Medicaid or SSI. However, the services are usually reserved for individuals with more significant disabilities when compared to SSI or basic Medicaid.

===Other expanded Medicaid services===
Medicaid offers many different services, including for those who are disabled. In addition to HCBS 1915(c) waiver services, there are other programs, depending on the state. Examples include [https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/home-community-based-services/home-community-based-services-authorities/community-first-choice-cfc-1915-k 1915(k) Community First Choice (CFC)], [https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/home-community-based-services/home-community-based-services-authorities/home-community-based-services-1915i 1915(i) State Plan HCBS], [https://www.macpac.gov/subtopic/1915b-waivers/ 1915(b) Managed LTSS], [https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/home-community-based-services/home-community-based-services-authorities/self-directed-personal-assistant-services-1915-j 1915(j) Self-Directed Personal Assistant Services], [https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/section-1115-demonstrations/about-section-1115-demonstrations 1115 Demonstration waivers], and [https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/long-term-services-supports/institutional-long-term-care/intermediate-care-facilities-individuals-intellectual-disability ICF/IID care].

===Health Insurance Premium Payment programs===
Most states have Health Insurance Premium Payment (HIPP) programs offered through Medicaid for adult children and other dependents who remain on their parent's private or employer health insurance plans. These programs will pay all or part of the employee contribution of the private or employer plan, and Medicaid becomes secondary to the private or employer plan. The state Medicaid program will only provide this reimbursement if they deem it economically beneficial for the state to do so. In many instances the entire family health insurance employee contribution can be reimbursed. In others, it may be limited to the employee contribution of the employee plus child option of the plan. The result is the family's private or employer plan becomes primary, and Medicaid becomes secondary, potentially picking up the out of pocket expenses from the employer plans.

Listings of state HIPP programs can be found [https://www.dol.gov/sites/dolgov/files/ebsa/laws-and-regulations/laws/chipra/model-notice.pdf here] and [https://www.joingivers.com/learn/hipp-program here].

===Employer health insurance programs===

The [https://www.healthcare.gov/glossary/affordable-care-act/ Affordable Care Act] requires many employers to provide health insurance, including family members up to 26 years old. A few states have laws that require state regulated employer health insurance programs to extend health insurance beyond the age of 26 for disabled dependents, under specific circumstances with specific criteria. While other states may not require it, some employers in other states may choose to provide this coverage.<ref>[https://blog.ifebp.org/age-26-insurance-mandate-and-disabled-adult-dependents/ IFEBP-Questions Parents Are Asking About the Age 26 Mandate and Disabled Adult Dependents]</ref> Families interested in this coverage should discuss with their employers well in advance of the disabled dependent's 26th birthday to determine potential eligibility.

==Savings strategies for disabled adults==

===Supplemental Needs Trusts===

A supplemental needs trust (SNT), also known as a [[trusts#Special Needs Trusts (SNTs)|special needs trust]]<ref group="note">The terms special needs trusts and supplemental needs trusts are now used interchangeably, although when they were originally conceived there was a difference.  Special Needs Trusts were considered the broad category to include 1st and 3rd party SNTs, while supplemental needs trusts were specifically 3rd party SNTs.

[https://specialneedsanswers.com/is-there-a-difference-between-supplemental-and-special-needs-trusts-16243 SNA-Supplemental vs. Special Needs Trusts: Any Difference?]</ref>, is a common way of providing resources for a disabled adult child. The main purpose of a supplemental needs trust is to provide resources in a way that does not interfere with any means-based government assistance. Because the trust is a separate legal entity, any resources that have been accumulated do not count against government benefits, provided the trust is set up and executed properly. They are referred to as "supplemental needs" trusts because they are intended to supplement, not replace, government assistance, such as SSI. Funds from supplemental needs trusts cannot be used for basic support such as housing and shelter (and food before 30 September, 2024) because that is what the government benefits are intended for.<ref group="note">The 209(b) Medicaid states may have differing criteria for in kind support relating to Medicaid eligibility. Research specific state rules.</ref> Using SNT funds for these basic needs is considered in-kind support and maintenance, and can reduce or eliminate benefits such as SSI or Medicaid, depending on the state. States have different rules for counting in-kind support and maintenance payments as income that may affect Medicaid eligibility. Additionally, 209(b) states may have statutory language or policies that prohibit ISM disbursements from a SNT that would have the effect of replacing, reducing, or substituting for publicly funded benefits (which would be relevant if receiving SSI).

Supplemental needs trusts are a specialized area, and it is a good idea to engage an estate planning or elder law attorney who has experience in this area.

There are two categories of SNTs:

# [https://smartasset.com/estate-planning/first-party-special-needs-trust First Party SNTs] - Also referred to as self-settled SNTs, these are trusts created by and for the disabled adult child. The disabled adult is considered the grantor as well as the beneficiary of the trust. The trust is funded with money belonging to the disabled child. The money could have come originally from an inheritance paid directly to the disabled child, an injury or medical settlement, or personal financial accounts owned by the disabled child. Specific attributes of a first party SNT include:
#* The beneficiary of a first-party SNT must have a documented disability recognized by the Social Security Administration.
#* First-party SNTs must be funded before the beneficiary reaches age 65, and no further assets can be transferred into the trust once the beneficiary reaches this age. The trust can remain established and provide benefits regardless of the beneficiary's age.
#* When the beneficiary of a first-party SNT dies, the trust is required to reimburse the government (to the extent possible) for medical expenses paid on the beneficiary's behalf.
#[https://specialneedsanswers.com/what-is-a-third-party-special-needs-trust-and-how-is-it-different-from-other-kinds-of-trusts-15111 Third Party SNTs] - These are funded by a third party, such as a parent or grandparent. The third party is the grantor of the trust. The trustee can be the grantor, or another third party, but typically should not be the disabled adult beneficiary. The disabled adult mostly likely will have no control over any of the funds in the trust and have no right to demand funds from the trust. If the beneficiary were allowed control of the funds, Social Security or the applicable government agency could view the trust funds as a countable resource, endangering the eligibility for the benefits. Specific attributes of a third party SNT:
#* While third party SNTs are typically for the benefit of disabled individuals, unlike a first party SNT, the beneficiary does not have to meet Social Security's definition of disabled for the trust to be valid. It has become a common practice to include SNT type language in many third party trusts, in case the beneficiary becomes disabled later in life.
#* Unlike first party SNTs, on the death of the disabled beneficiary, third party SNTs assets are not available to Medicaid for potential reimbursement/recovery.
#* While technically not necessary, third party SNTs usually have language indicating that the trust is for the supplemental needs of the disabled beneficiary. This signals to applicable government agencies as well as third party trustees that the trust is specifically intended for the supplemental needs of the disabled adult and funds should be distributed in a way not to endanger government benefits if applicable.
#* These trusts should generally give the trustee broad discretionary powers, including to make distributions that disqualify the beneficiary from government benefits, if it is in the beneficiary's best interest to do so. By giving the trustee broad discretionary powers, this demonstrates to any relevant reviewing agency that the beneficiary has no control over the trust assets.
#* SNTs as a general rule should not mandate the trustee to make specific distributions from the trust, because the distributions could then be viewed as in-kind support, or an unwanted distribution could leave the beneficiary with countable resources that negate the means tested benefit.
#* Notwithstanding any of the above, some states may have specific rules as to language that should be included or the level of discretion allowed. Always consult state laws and rules.
#* Third party SNTs may be set to be funded either before or after passing of the parents. In some cases they are set up while the parents to receive expected gifts or inheritances from other parties, such as grandparents. In other cases the expectation is for the trust to be funded after one or both of the parents death, either through a [[Trusts#Testamentary Trusts|testamentary trust]] in a will or a sub-trust within a [[Trusts#Revocable Living Trusts (RLTs)|revocable living trust]].

Advantages of Supplemental Needs Trusts:

* Allows for the accumulation of unlimited resources for the beneficiary without endangering government benefit eligibility.
* Because most funded SNTs will likely be irrevocable trusts, as with any properly drafted and implemented irrevocable trust, trust assets usually have a higher degree of protection against potential creditors, divorcing spouses and keep the assets out of beneficiary's future estate, avoiding future federal and state estate taxes, if applicable.
* If the trust is a third party SNT, the resources are not available for recovery by Medicaid on the death of the disabled beneficiary.

Disadvantages of Supplemental Needs Trusts:

* They can be expensive to set up, likely costing at least several thousand dollars to draft and set up.
* The tax rates for trusts are compressed, and the 37% tax rate is reached with only $15,600 (in 2025)<ref group="note">2025 Trust tax rates:

$0 – $3,150: 10%

$3,150 – $11,450: 24%

$11,450 – $15,650: 35%

$15,650+: 37%

[https://www.ardentrust.com/insights/trust-tax-rates-deductions Arden Trust - Trust Tax Rates & Deductions in 2025]</ref>  and $16,000 (in 2026) <ref group="note">'''For estates and trusts:'''

If taxable income is less than $3,300; the tax is 10% of taxable income

If taxable income is over $3,300 but not over $11,700; the tax is $330.00 plus 24% of the excess over $3,300

If taxable income is over $11,700 but not over $16,000; the tax is $2,346.00 plus 35% of the excess over $11,700

If taxable income is over $16,000; the tax is $3,851.00 plus 37% of the excess over $16,000

[https://tax.thomsonreuters.com/news/key-2026-figures-calculated-by-thomson-reuters-checkpoint-based-on-inflation-data-now-available/ Thompsons Reuters - Key 2026 Figures Calculated by Thomson Reuters Checkpoint Based on Inflation Data Now Available]

</ref> of trust income retained in the trust.  However, distributed income from the trust is taxable at the disabled adult's individual tax rate, which will usually be lower, but as always distributions should be made in a way not to endanger government benefits. (Most supplemental needs trusts also qualify as [https://www.investopedia.com/qualified-disability-trust-5217846 Qualified Disability Trusts (QDisT)], and will receive personal exemption, which reduces the trust taxable income. The 2025 QDisT exemption is $5,100. <ref>[https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/the-voice/taxation-of-special-needs-trusts-an-overview/ Special Needs Alliance - Taxation of Special Needs Trusts: An Overview]</ref>)
* Once the irrevocable trust is funded, the trust will require a trust tax return and individual trust accounting. Most people will need to engage outside professional services for help with these tasks.

===ABLE accounts===
{{Main|529-ABLE plan}}

An ABLE (Achieving a Better Life Experience) account, also known as a 529A, is a 529 style plan for certain adults with qualifying disabilities. Like a [[529 plan|529 college plan]], a 529-ABLE plan allows qualifying individuals to save money where future growth is tax free (similar to a [[Roth IRA]]), provided the future distributions are for qualifying disability expenses. What makes the 529-ABLE unique is that assets saved in these accounts, up to a specified limit in some cases, do not count against government benefits such as SSI and Medicaid. Also, unlike a 529 college account, which can be owned by a third party to the beneficiary such as a parent, the ABLE account is owned by the beneficiary, although a parent or third party may be designated to manage the account if necessary.

In order to qualify for a 529-ABLE, the beneficiary must have a qualifying disability. An individual who has been deemed as disabled by the Social Security Administration (SSA) or any state agencies authorized to make these determinations meets the definition of disabled. Alternatively, a physician can diagnose a qualifying disability. The disabled individual must have contracted the disability before age 26 in order to participate in an ABLE plan. As of January 1, 2026 the age is increased and disability must have happened before age 46.

ABLE plans are administered by the states, and as of 2025 only a few states do not offer a plan. Most of the state plans allow out-of-state residents to also participate. Some of the plans are administered by brokerage firms such as Fidelity or Vanguard.

The maximum contribution to an ABLE account in a year, from all sources, is the same amount as the federal gift tax exclusion, which is $19,000 for 2025 and remains the same in 2026. If the beneficiary works, the annual contribution limits can be higher.<ref group="note">As of 2025, an ABLE Account Owner who resides in the continental U.S. and who works and does NOT participate in an employer sponsored retirement plan – within that calendar year – may contribute up to an additional $15,060 from their earnings into their ABLE account. It is higher for residents of Alaska: $18,810 and Hawaii: $17,310. See: [https://www.ablenrc.org/able-account-contribution-limits-2025/ ABLE Account Contribution Limits (2025)]</ref> Contributions to the account can continue until the balance receives the maximum balance, after which contributions can no longer be made, but existing balances may continue to grow. The maximums are determined by the states, and are typically the same as the maximum balance of a 529 college savings plan account. The state maximums typically range from $500,000 to $550,000. However, if the disabled adult is receiving SSI, the balance must be kept below $100,000, or else SSI eligibility will be lost; the ABLE amounts do not affect Medicaid eligibility, so individuals on programs such as SSDI-DAC do not need to worry about the $100,000 SSI limit.

Distributions from ABLE accounts can be used for Qualified Disability Expenses, which include a broad array of expenses. Qualified disability expenses (QDE) are expenses made for the benefit of the designated beneficiary and related to his or her disability, including, but not limited to:<ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/ssi/spotlights/spot-able.html#:~:text=Qualified%20disability%20expenses%20(QDE)%20are,Basic%20living%20expenses. SSA- ABLE-Qualified Disability Expenses]</ref><ref>[https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2015-title26/pdf/USCODE-2015-title26-subtitleA-chap1-subchapF-partVIII-sec529A.pdf U.S. Government. “Section 529A(e)(5) of the ABLE Act, 26 U.S. Code 529A(e)(5).”]</ref>

*Education;
* Housing;{{#tag:ref|Housing is considered a QDE but must be spent in the same month as withdrawn from the ABLE account:<ref>[https://secure.ssa.gov/apps10/poms.nsf/lnx/0501130740 SSA -Program Operations Manual System (POMS)-TN 131 (07-25)-SI 01130.740 Achieving a Better Life Experience (ABLE) Accounts, #2]</ref>
{{blockquote|Count a distribution for a housing expense or for an expense that is not a QDE as a resource, if the designated beneficiary retains the distribution into the month following the month of receipt. If the designated beneficiary spends the distribution within the month of receipt, there is no effect on eligibility. Apply normal SSI resource counting rules and exclusions to items purchased with funds from an ABLE account.

'''EXAMPLE: Retained distribution intended for housing expenses is a resource'''

Amy takes a distribution of $500 from their ABLE account in May to pay a housing expense for June. They deposit the $500 into their checking account in May, withdraws $500 in cash on June 3, and pay their landlord. This distribution is a housing expense and part of their checking account balance as of June 1, which makes it a countable resource for the month of June.}}|group="note"}}
* Food;<ref group="note">“However, for ABLE purposes, food is considered a qualified disability expense (basic living expense), but not a housing expense”. Source: [https://secure.ssa.gov/apps10/poms.nsf/lnx/0501130740 SSA -Program Operations Manual System (POMS)-TN 131 (07-25)-SI 01130.740 Achieving a Better Life Experience (ABLE) Accounts, #9]</ref>
* Transportation;
* Employment training and support;
* Assistive technology and related services;
* Health;
* Prevention and wellness;
* Financial management and administrative services;
* Legal fees;
* Expenses for ABLE account oversight and monitoring;
* Funeral and burial; and,
* Basic living expenses.

While ABLE account funds can be held indefinitely and belong to the disabled adult account owner, on the death of the beneficiary Federal law allows Medicaid to pursue Medicaid funds spent on behalf of the beneficiary from remaining funds in the ABLE account. However, multiple states have passed legislation limiting the state's Medicaid system from doing so for in state participants.

Although ABLE accounts and third party special needs trusts are sometimes viewed as alternatives to each other, they can actually complement each other if they are both set up. SNTs may make distributions directly to the ABLE account, as long as total contributions for the year do not exceed the federal gift tax thresholds ($19,000 for 2025 and 2026). This can be advantageous in different ways:

* SNTs cannot make distributions for housing expenses, while an ABLE account can, provided the expenditure is made in the same month of the distribution. Money could be distributed to the ABLE account, then disbursed from the ABLE account for a housing expense.
* Because trust tax rates are compressed and likely higher than the individual's personal tax rate, it can be advantageous to distribute trust income to take advantage of the lower personal rates. Trust distributions should however only be used for appropriate purposes and almost never should be made directly to the beneficiary, because the distributions could be deemed in-kind, or it may result in an asset balance exceeding the $2,000 SSI limit. In these cases the distribution could be made to the ABLE account, allowing for taxation at personal tax rates, but avoiding countable income or resources.

Advantages of 529-ABLE:
* Amounts can accumulate and grow income tax free, if eventually used for Qualified Disabilty expenses.
* Accounts generally have low fees.
* Funds in account and qualified distributions do not count against or disqualify from government benefits, including SSI.
* Unlike Supplemental Needs Trusts, housing expenses can be paid out of an ABLE account provided they are spent the same month as the distribution.
* 529-ABLE accounts are flexible and typically do not require additional professional resources to maintain.
* ABLE accounts can be used in conjunction with supplemental needs trusts to increase flexibility.
Disadvantages of 529-ABLE accounts:
* Further contributions are disallowed after the ABLE account reaches its state statutory maximum.
* Balances over $100,000 in the account are considered countable resources towards SSI and may reduce or disqualify beneficiary from SSI.
* Federal law allows Medicaid to attempt recovery of Medicaid expenses from the ABLE account after the death of the disabled participant. However, some states have chosen to limit or prohibit this type of recovery for in state residents.
* Use of ABLE funds for non QDEs can cause federal taxation and penalties, as well as potentially be treated as countable income for SSI.
* If the beneficiary is deemed no longer disabled at some point in the future, the account will eventually need to be closed and distributions the following year become taxable and subject to withdrawal penalties.<ref>[https://www.urblaw.com/what-happens-to-an-able-account-if-the-beneficiary-is-no-longer-disabled/#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%20only%20for%20a%20limited%20time.,as%20if%20the%20beneficiary%20were%20still%20eligible. ABLE Accounts: When the Beneficiary Is No Longer Disabled]</ref>

===Pooled trusts===
[https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/pooled_trust Pooled trusts] are trusts set up by non-profits for disabled and special needs adults.<ref>[https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/blog/when-should-you-consider-a-pooled-trust/ Special Needs Alliance- When Should You Consider a Pooled Trust?]</ref> All of the various participants money is pooled for investment purposes, but individual sub accounts are maintained for each participant. Distributions are made from the sub accounts for qualifying expenses. Like Supplemental Needs trusts, they can be first party or third party.

Advantages:
* Pooled trusts are professionally managed.
* Pooled trusts can take relatively smaller contributions vs an individual trust managed by a corporate trustee.
* They can be set up quickly if needed in cases such as an unexpected inheritance.
* There is no need for a court appointed trustee.

Disadvantages:
* There are administrative fees involved.
* Due to the pooled nature there is less individual control of assets.
* On the beneficiary's death, the funds will either be paid back to Medicaid or remain in the pool.
* While rare, there have been instances of fraud in this space.<ref>[https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/florida-nonprofit-founder-and-accountant-charged-stealing-over-100m-special-needs-victims U.S. Dept of Justice - Florida Nonprofit Founder and Accountant Charged with Stealing Over $100M from Special Needs Victims]</ref>

===Comparing SNTs, ABLE accounts, and pooled trusts===

The following document contains a comparison of ABLE accounts, Supplemental Needs Trusts and Pooled Trusts: [https://www.ablenrc.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/2025_SNT_ABLE_comparison-FINAL-1-1.pdf ABLE Account, Special Needs and Pooled Trust Comparison Chart]

==Saving strategies for parents==

In many cases, parents plan to save additional money on their own and pass it to their disabled adult children upon their deaths, typically to a third party special needs trust. Additional considerations for such savings are as follows:

'''Taxable investments''': Parents may choose to save for their adult children in a taxable investment or brokerage account. One common strategy is to invest in highly tax efficient index funds and ETFs, then on a parent's death take advantage of the capital gains [[step-up in basis]]. These funds would then likely flow to a third party SNT for the benefit of the disabled adult child.

'''Roth IRAs''': [[Roth IRA|Roth IRAs]] can be a great way to save for a disabled adult child's future. There are no RMDs, the funds are not taxed during the parent's lifetime, and if they pass to the child's third party SNT on the parent’s death, they will be moved to an inherited IRA within the SNT. Roth funds held within the trusts also avoid higher trust tax rates, which quickly reach the maximum 37% tax rate. Roths in special needs trusts are highly flexible, distributions can be made as needed, avoiding trust taxes and allowing maximum flexibility when distributing to avoid any issues with any needs based government benefit programs. While inherited IRAs in trusts often have required minimum distributions, including Roths, in this particular instance a [https://www.morningstar.com/retirement/ed-slott-how-eligible-designated-beneficiaries-changed qualifying disabled child should qualify as an eligible designated beneficiary(EDB)], allowing the adult child to spread the RMDs over their remaining actuarial lifetime, resulting in relatively small RMDs. Because Roth distributions are not taxable, they can remain in the trust (assuming the trust is an [https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/accumulation_trust accumulation trust]) without an immediate tax impact and maintain the protections of the SNT. Given the flexibility of Roths in a future SNT, parents may choose to do Roth conversions during their lifetimes.

[https://paytaxeslater.com/ James Lange], a CPA, financial advisor and attorney, and also the father of a disabled child, has [https://disabledchildplanning.com/ written a book on this subject]. One of his primary points is the benefits of accumulating assets in Roth, including Roth conversions, and leaving Roth IRAs to a disabled child EDB in a special needs trust, due to the flexibility, tax efficiency and long term compounded growth potential of a Roth over many decades between the parent and the child.

'''Traditional IRAs''': Passing traditional inherited IRAs to special needs trusts has some complications and requires care, but in some cases can provide an opportunity for significant income tax savings. If the parent was originally in a relatively higher tax bracket, once passed to an inherited IRA inside an SNT, and assuming the disabled adult child qualifies as an EDB, the lifetime stretch can result in comparatively small RMDs. If the trust is a qualified disability trust (QDisT), a portion of the RMD can remain in the trust tax free. Amounts in excess of that can be distributed out of the trust and will be taxed at the child's income tax rate, which will presumably be low or even zero. However, the distributions be made in a way not to jeopardize any means tested government benefits. The distributions would need to be spent on non-ISM expenses, or alternatively transferred to an ABLE account. The distribution should typically not go directly to the disabled child as it could be deemed in-kind support and maintenance, and should not be accumulated by the child, which could lead to countable resources. Those on SSDI-DAC rather than SSI may be able to avoid some of these pitfalls. 

The net result is the parent may have contributed funds into the traditional IRA when at a high marginal tax rate, but if the future SNT RMDs remain below approximately $20,000 there may be no income tax when distributed. 

'''Example-Traditional Inherited IRA RMD in SNT''' 

The 2025 QdisT exemption is $5,100.<ref>[https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/the-voice/taxation-of-special-needs-trusts-an-overview/ SNA-https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/the-voice/taxation-of-special-needs-trusts-an-overview/]</ref> The 2025 single standard deduction is $15,750. Combined, the two equal $20,850. Assuming the disabled adult taxpayer and EDB, as well as the SNT, had no other taxable income, $20,850 of RMD could avoid tax, by retaining $5,100 of income within the trust and distributing $15,750 outside of the trust. The single life expectancy of a hypothetical 57 disabled EDB would be 29.8 years. As such, there could be up to a $621,330 traditional IRA balance in the SNT and the first year RMD would be tax free. An 85 year old grandparent passing an inherited IRA to a disabled 35 year old adult EDB would get a 50.5 year stretch,<ref>[https://www.fidelity.com/bin-public/060_www_fidelity_com/documents/retirement/single-life-expectancy-table.pdf Fidelity-Single Life Table]</ref> allowing for a potential IRA balance of over $1&nbsp;million with a first year non taxable RMD ($1,000,000/50.5 =$19,801).

This approach requires a properly drafted accumulation trust or SNT, and distributions need to be handled with care. It also requires a trustee who has the skill and the knowledge to execute this. Because there are annual RMDs generating taxable income, there are frequent decision points, increasing complexity and decreasing the margin of error. Another potential downside of this strategy is if the beginning IRA balance is large, and the growth of the IRA funds significantly exceeds the modest annual RMDs, RMDs will grow, forcing a choice between leaving the money in trust at high trust tax rates, or distributing greater than desired amounts from the trust. Finally, there are anecdotal reports that the taxable income generated by the trust or trust distributions may mistakenly be deemed as countable income by reviewing agencies, requiring intervention and correction.<ref>{{Forum link|title=‪ Planning for disabled adult children - proposed wiki page|p= 8578903|author=Poster typical.investor|date=November 13, 2025}}</ref>

==Estate planning for disabled adult children==
Passing assets on to disabled adult children requires special care and attention from an estate planning perspective. The parents' plans in these situations require trust and estates attorneys or elder law attorneys with specific knowledge in this area. 

===Common estate planning issues===
* Use of Trusts: Estate planners will typically recommend leaving assets to disabled heirs in trusts, not only for typical trust protections like protection from creditors, but also the use of special needs trusts as addressed previously.
* Exercise extreme care or avoid using designated beneficiaries where possible: one incorrect or sub-optimal designated beneficiary, whether primary or contingent, or even a per stirpes designation, can override a carefully designed estate plan or unintentionally disqualify a disabled beneficiary from certain needs based government benefits.
* Inherited IRAs and EDBs: One specific area with unique attributes when planning for disabled heirs is when passing on IRAs and 401k style retirement plans. The Secure Act, and later Secure Act 2.0, differentiated disabled and chronically ill adults as Eligible Designated Beneficiaries (EDBs). The result is unlike most non spouse heirs, who will need to liquidate their inherited IRA within 10 years, EDBs can still spread their required minimum distributions over their remaining lifetime, creating estate planning opportunities to minimize income taxes over decades. Inherited IRAs, especially within Supplemental Needs Trusts, is a complicated area within estate planning and requires estate planning attorneys experienced in this discipline.
* To reiterate the importance of getting designated beneficiaries right, as well as taking advantage of EDB's extended stretch in a special needs trust, advance planning is needed to make sure the beneficiaries are set up correctly. For example, assume one parent dies, had their spouse as the primary beneficiary of the IRA, and had the SNT for the benefit of the EDB contingent beneficiary. At that point, the IRA passes to the spouse, and may be rolled into an IRA in the spouse's name, but the deceased parent's contingent beneficiary then becomes irrelevant. In order for the eventual inherited IRA to get to the EDB, the surviving spouse must subsequently name the EDB's SNT as the beneficiary of that IRA. If the surviving spouse directly names the EDB, but not the trust, then means based benefits may be in danger. If the surviving spouse fails to name a beneficiary at all, then the IRA passes to the estate and may have to be liquidated in either five years, or at a term that is significantly shorter than the EDB's actuarial lifespan.<ref>[https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/the-voice/naming-a-special-needs-trust-as-beneficiary-of-your-ira-or-retirement-plan-3/ SNA-Naming a Special Needs Trust as Beneficiary of Your IRA or Retirement Plan]</ref>

===After parents die===

Another important decision for estate planning is who will take over when the disabled adult child's parents die or become incapacitated. First of all, a decision will need to be made who will look over the disabled adult if they are unable to take care of themselves. If guardianship is involved, successor guardians should be named as part of the estate plan. As to the financial administration, the appointment of a [[Trusts#Trustees|trustee]] is also important. Given the complexity of the subject matter, in many cases a professional fiduciary may be more appropriate.<ref>[https://www.specialneedsalliance.org/blog/do-i-really-need-a-professional-trustee-for-my-special-needs-trust/ SNA-Do I Really Need A Professional Trustee For My Special Needs Trust?]</ref> One option is to appoint a [https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/corporate_trustee corporate trustee]. There are many corporate trustees who have experience in administration of estates left in special needs trusts.  In some instances where one spouse has handled the financial and administrative issues while the other is less experienced on these matters, passing some of the resources to the trust and engaging a professional trustee upon death of the first spouse may make sense.

==Federal income tax considerations==

===Disabled adult child as dependent qualifying child or qualifying relative ===

Qualifying child or qualifying relative status allows the child to be claimed as a dependent of the parent or other qualifying caregiver.  As a dependent, the supporting family may be eligible for additional tax benefits:

The six IRS requirements for '''qualifying child''' are:<ref>[https://support.taxslayer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360015899451-What-are-the-requirements-for-a-Qualifying-Child-used-to-determine-dependent-status Taxslayer-What are the requirements for a "Qualifying Child' (used to determine dependent status)?]</ref>

* '''Relationship''' – must be the taxpayer’s child or stepchild (by blood or adoption), foster child, sibling or step-sibling, or a descendant of any of these.
* '''Age''' – Unlike non-disabled children, permanently and totally disabled children can qualify regardless of age.
* '''Residence''' – the child must have lived with the taxpayer for more than 6 months of the tax year. Exceptions are made for the children of separated or divorced parents.  If a child was born or died during the year, they are considered to have lived with you the entire year.
* '''Support''' – refers to the child’s income, which must not have provided more than half of the child’s support for the tax year<ref group="note">- SSI and SSDI received directly by the child count as the child’s own support

- Distributions from a 1st-party SNT (d4A / (A)(C)) count as the child’s support

- Distributions from a 3rd-party SNT generally count as support provided by the parent (not the child)

- ABLE distributions - for qualified expenses count as child support provided by the child, because ABLE belongs to the child.</ref>
* '''Joint Return''' – the child cannot file a joint return, unless the return is filed only to claim a refund of withholding 
* '''Citizenship''' – the child must be a US citizen, US resident alien, and the child must have a SSN by the date the return is filed.
Requirements for a '''qualifying relative''':<ref>[https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/dependents IRS-Dependents]</ref>

* '''Not a qualifying child''': Isn't your qualifying child or the qualifying child of any other taxpayer
* '''Member of household or relationship''': Lives with you all year as a member of your household or is a specific type of relative
* '''Gross income''': Has gross income under $5,050
* '''Support''': Gets more than half their financial support from you

'''Potential tax benefits as a qualifying child or qualifying relative:'''

'''Credit for other dependents'''- while the child tax credit (CTC) is only available for those under 17, a dependent disabled adult child qualifies for the credit for other dependents.  The maximum credit is $500 and starts to phase out at $200,000 AGI and $400,000 MFJ.<ref>[https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/child-tax-credit IRS-Child Tax Credi]</ref>

'''Child and dependent care credit''' - this credit is available for dependent disabled adult children who are incapable of self-care and who live with you for more than half of the year.<ref>[https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/child-and-dependent-care-credit-information IRS-Child and Dependent Care Credit information]</ref> For tax year 2025, the maximum amount of care expenses you're allowed to claim is $3,000 for one person, or $6,000 for two or more people. The percentage of your qualified expenses that you can claim as a credit ranges from 20% to 35%.<ref>[https://turbotax.intuit.com/tax-tips/family/the-ins-and-outs-of-the-child-and-dependent-care-tax-credit/amp/L2H7rzUWc TurboTax - The Ins and Outs of the Child and Dependent Care Credit]</ref>

'''Head of Household filing status''' - having a qualifying dependent adult child will enable a single parent to file head of household status, which is advantageous compared to single filing status.<ref>[https://smartasset.com/taxes/what-you-need-to-know-about-filing-head-of-household Smart Asset-Head of Household Filing Status: Definition, Rules and Requirements]</ref>

'''Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC)''' - EITC is available for lower income individuals and families. The additional benefit is available for a qualifying child dependent (not qualifying relative).<ref>[https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/earned-income-tax-credit/disability-and-the-earned-income-tax-credit-eitc IRS-Disability and the Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC)]</ref> A qualifying child can increase EITC a maximum of approximately $3700 as of 2025, as well significantly increasing the maximum AGI limit for EITC.<ref>[https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/earned-income-tax-credit/earned-income-and-earned-income-tax-credit-eitc-tables IRS-Earned income and Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC) tables]</ref>

'''Qualifying Surviving Spouse filing status''' - Having a qualified dependent disabled adult child could make a surviving spouse eligible for the [https://apps.irs.gov/app/understandingTaxes/hows/tax_tutorials/mod05/tt_mod05_07.jsp Qualifying Surviving Spouse status] (formerly known as the Qualifying Widow or Qualifying Widower tax status).  This can be claimed for the two tax years after the death of your spouse. However, you can’t use it for the year your spouse passed away.

To qualify for the Qualifying Surviving Spouse filing status, you must meet these four requirements:<ref>[https://www.hrblock.com/tax-center/filing/personal-tax-planning/qualifying-widow-or-widower/?amp H&R Block-Qualifying surviving spouse: What’s the tax filing status after the death of your spouse?]</ref>

* You qualified for Married Filing Jointly with your spouse for the year they died. (It doesn’t matter if you actually filed as Married Filing Jointly.)
* You didn’t remarry.
* You have a child, stepchild, or adopted child you claim as your tax dependent. This doesn’t apply to a foster child.
* You paid more than half the cost of maintaining your home. This must be the main home of your dependent child for the entire year, except for temporary absences.

Qualifying Surviving Spouse status entitles you to use both of these:

* Married Filing Jointly tax rates — However, you’re not entitled to file a joint return after the year of death.
* The same standard deduction amount as Married Filing Jointly — Only use this if you don’t itemize deductions.

==Other topics==

===Conservatorship and guardianship===
Guardianship and conservatorship is an issue many parents or caregivers will face when caring for a disabled adult child. It is a complex topic, requiring specialized legal expertise, and some aspects of it may go beyond the scope of Bogleheads typical subject matter. It can be a controversial topic in some circles regarding its desirability compared to alternatives. Regardless, it does however obviously have financial and estate planning implications.

Different states use different terminology when using the terms guardianship and conservatorship. In many states, guardianship refers to personal and medical decisions, whereas conservatorship refers to financial decisions.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.legalzoom.com/articles/conservatorship-vs-guardianship| title=Conservatorship vs. Guardianship: Key Differences and Legal Guidance| publisher=LegalZoom| accessdate=August 29, 2025}}</ref> In states such as California, guardianship refers to care of minors, and conservatorship to incapacitated adults. In Texas it is the opposite; conservatorship relates to minors ,and guardianship to adults.<ref group="note">In Texas, guardian of the person refers to day to day care, whereas guardian of the estate refers to management of financial interests.</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.ruelaslaw.com/guardian-of-the-estate-vs-guardian-of-the-person| title=Guardian of the Estate vs. Guardian of the Person| publisher=Ruelas Andino Law| accessdate=August 29, 2025}}</ref>

There may be different types of guardianships; again this varies by state. In Texas for example, there is a [https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/guardian_of_the_person guardian of the person] and guardian of the estate. The guardian of the person handles most personal and day to day living issues, such as where the ward lives, whether the ward marries entering into contractual agreements. The [https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/guardian_of_the_estate guardian of an estate] handles the management of financial assets of the ward, beyond a minimal amount. In the case of a disabled adult child, a guardian of the estate may be unnecessary, because ideally due to government benefits, most or all of the assets are outside the estate in supplemental needs trusts, ABLE accounts or other means of ownership.

Guardianship or conservatorship is granted by a court, and typically has to be renewed periodically, often annually. The renewal can be a simple filing in some states, or more complex in others.

Alternatives to guardianship include [[Estate planning#Power of Attorney|powers of attorney]], such as durable power of attorney and health care proxy, as well as other arrangements such as [https://supporteddecisions.org/about-supported-decision-making/ supported decision making]. These other options generally assume legal competency and are less restrictive than a guardianship or conservatorship. Which of these is most appropriate is entirely dependent on the individual situation.

===Receiving an unexpected inheritance===

In most cases receiving an inheritance is considered a positive event. However, for a disabled adult on needs based benefits if not handled correctly it can be at best a headache and at worst disastrous. The income from the inheritance could be viewed as disqualifying income or resources, resulting in benefits being stopped.

The best case scenario is to notify all applicable parties in advance to either not give to the disabled individual directly, or to give in a coordinated fashion via a special needs trust, ABLE account or other appropriate means. Experts in the area will often advise parents to communicate in advance to relatives who may choose to leave an inheritance of the consequences of doing this.

If an unexpected inheritance is received, the family should usually not cash any checks, commingle any of the inherited funds with other funds or spend any of the money right away. What they should do is immediately contact an estate planner. Other paths to avoid would be disclaiming the inheritance, as the government agency may view this as acceptance and a transfer. Also, hoping the applicable government agency will not notice is a bad idea, because failing to notify the agency is likely a breach of agency rules. What an attorney is likely to advise is to put it into a first party special needs trust, a pooled trust or an ABLE account (if the balance is relatively modest).<ref>[https://specialneedsanswers.com/should-an-ssi-recipient-simply-refuse-an-inheritance--15473 SNA-Should an SSI Recipient Refuse an Inheritance?]</ref>

===Family opportunity mortgage===
A [https://www.investopedia.com/what-is-a-family-opportunity-mortgage-how-it-works-eligibility-and-benefits-8654115 family opportunity mortgage] is a mortgage that a family member, for example a parent, can take out on a home for the benefit of a disabled or elderly family member. The person taking out the mortgage owns the house. Unlike most primary home mortgages, the person taking out the mortgage does not have to live in the house. Also, the mortgage interest is tax deductible, similar to a primary home mortgage, assuming the mortgage holder is otherwise able to itemize deductions.

These mortgages are backed by Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, and the borrower should be able to obtain rates similar to a primary home mortgage, and unlike the higher rates associated with a second home. These mortgages may go by other names other than Family Opportunity Mortgage.

===Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program===

Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP), formerly referred to as "Food Stamps", is a nutritional assistance program available for those with incomes below certain thresholds, as well as the disabled. Some individuals who are on SSI may also be potentially eligible for SNAP. However, eligibility for SNAP is not only dependent upon the means testing of the individual, but also others in the same household, making it more restrictive than other programs available for the disabled.<ref>[https://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/eligibility/elderly-disabled-special-rules SNAP Special Rules for the Elderly or Disabled]</ref><ref>[https://www.ssa.gov/pubs/EN-05-10101.pdf SSA-Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) Facts]</ref> After age 22, an adult living with their parents can be considered a separate SNAP household so long as they separate their food purchasing, preparation and consumption.

===Veteran's Benefits===

For certain qualifying disabled adult children of veterans,<ref>[https://www.howvadisabilityratingswork.com/resources/benefits/helpless-child Child Incapable of Self Support Over the Age of 18 (Helpless Child)]</ref> there are programs available that may be helpful.<ref>[https://www.hillandponton.com/benefits-for-grown-child-of-veteran/ Can a Grown Child of a Veteran Get DIC Benefits?]</ref><ref>[https://www.va.gov/family-and-caregiver-benefits/survivor-compensation/survivors-pension/ VA-Survivors Pension]</ref><ref>[https://www.va.gov/family-and-caregiver-benefits/health-and-disability/champva/ VA-CHAMPVA benefits]</ref><ref>[https://www.benefits.va.gov/fiduciary/ VA Fiduciary Program]</ref><ref>[https://www.knowva.ebenefits.va.gov/system/templates/selfservice/va_ssnew/help/customer/locale/en-US/portal/554400000001018/content/554400000177975/M21-1-Part-X-Subpart-ii-Chapter-6-Section-B-A-Childs-Permanent-Incapacity-for-Self-Support? VA-M21-1, Part X, Subpart ii, Chapter 6, Section B - A Child’s Permanent Incapacity for Self-Support]</ref><ref>[https://www.va.gov/family-and-caregiver-benefits/survivor-compensation/dependency-indemnity-compensation/ VA-About VA DIC for spouses, dependents, and parents]</ref><ref>[https://www.va.gov/family-and-caregiver-benefits/health-and-disability/ VA - Health and disability benefits for family and caregivers]</ref><ref>[https://www.congress.gov/crs-product/RS22483 Congress-Health Care for Dependents and Survivors of Veterans]</ref>

